useMemo is a React Hook used to memoize (cache) expensive calculations so they are not recalculated on every render.

Why use useMemo?

Normally, whenever a component re-renders, all code inside it runs again.

Example:

function App() {
  const [count, setCount] = useState(0);

  const expensiveValue = calculateLargeData(); // Runs every render

  return (
    <>
      <h2>{count}</h2>
      <button onClick={() => setCount(count + 1)}>
        Increment
      </button>
    </>
  );
}

Even if only count changes, calculateLargeData() runs again.

useMemo prevents unnecessary recalculations.

Syntax
const memoizedValue = useMemo(() => {
  return expensiveCalculation();
}, [dependencies]);
Parameters
First argument → Function that returns a value.
Second argument → Dependency array.

React recalculates only when dependencies change.

Example 1: Basic useMemo
import { useState, useMemo } from "react";

function App() {
  const [count, setCount] = useState(0);

  const square = useMemo(() => {
    console.log("Calculating...");
    return count * count;
  }, [count]);

  return (
    <div>
      <h2>Count: {count}</h2>
      <h2>Square: {square}</h2>

      <button onClick={() => setCount(count + 1)}>
        Increment
      </button>
    </div>
  );
}

export default App;
Output
Count: 2
Square: 4

When count changes, square is recalculated.

Example 2: Prevent Expensive Calculation
import { useState, useMemo } from "react";

function App() {
  const [count, setCount] = useState(0);
  const [name, setName] = useState("");

  const expensiveCalculation = (num) => {
    console.log("Running expensive calculation");

    for (let i = 0; i < 1000000000; i++) {}

    return num * 2;
  };

  const result = useMemo(() => {
    return expensiveCalculation(count);
  }, [count]);

  return (
    <div>
      <h2>Result: {result}</h2>

      <button onClick={() => setCount(count + 1)}>
        Increment Count
      </button>

      <input
        type="text"
        value={name}
        onChange={(e) => setName(e.target.value)}
        placeholder="Enter name"
      />
    </div>
  );
}

export default App;
Without useMemo

Changing the input triggers the expensive calculation again.

With useMemo

Changing the input only updates name.

Expensive calculation runs only when count changes.

Example 3: Filtering a List
import { useState, useMemo } from "react";

function App() {
  const [search, setSearch] = useState("");

  const users = [
    "John",
    "David",
    "Priya",
    "Kumar",
    "Alice"
  ];

  const filteredUsers = useMemo(() => {
    console.log("Filtering users");

    return users.filter(user =>
      user.toLowerCase().includes(search.toLowerCase())
    );
  }, [search]);

  return (
    <div>
      <input
        value={search}
        onChange={(e) => setSearch(e.target.value)}
      />

      <ul>
        {filteredUsers.map((user, index) => (
          <li key={index}>{user}</li>
        ))}
      </ul>
    </div>
  );
}

export default App;

The filtering logic runs only when search changes.

useMemo vs useEffect
useMemo	useEffect
Returns a value	Does not return a value
Used for calculations	Used for side effects
Runs during rendering	Runs after rendering
Caches computed values	Performs API calls, DOM updates
Example
const total = useMemo(() => {
  return price * quantity;
}, [price, quantity]);
useEffect(() => {
  fetchUsers();
}, []);
useMemo vs useCallback
useMemo

Caches a value

const total = useMemo(() => price * quantity, [price, quantity]);
useCallback

Caches a function

const handleClick = useCallback(() => {
  console.log("Clicked");
}, []);
When to Use useMemo

✅ Expensive calculations

✅ Large list filtering

✅ Sorting data

✅ Derived values from state

✅ Performance optimization

When NOT to Use useMemo

❌ For simple calculations

const sum = a + b;

No need for useMemo.

❌ Everywhere in the application

Overusing useMemo can actually reduce performance.

Interview Questions
1. What is useMemo?

useMemo is a React Hook that memoizes a computed value and recalculates it only when its dependencies change.

2. Why use useMemo?

To avoid expensive recalculations and improve performance.

3. What does useMemo return?

A memoized value.

4. Difference between useMemo and useCallback?
useMemo → Memoizes a value.
useCallback → Memoizes a function.
5. Does useMemo prevent re-rendering?

No. It only prevents recalculating a value. The component still re-renders when state or props change.
